<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,225,1179]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis box="[151,381,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body light brown to yellow, legs and antennae yellow, forewing pale with base and veins slightly yellow. Head strongly reticulate, cheeks almost parallel but sharply constricted to basal neck (
<figureCitation box="[1348,1420,264,290]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[1403,1420,264,290]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
); ocellar hump scarcely overhanging inter-antennal region; without major setae. Antennae slender, 
<number box="[1410,1427,302,328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="6.0">6</number>
- segmented, V–VII closely fused, VIII distinct (
<figureCitation box="[700,770,341,367]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[754,770,341,367]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
); sensoria on III and IV short and simple. Pronotum with two transverse bands of round to oval reticulation (
<figureCitation box="[768,843,380,406]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[825,843,380,406]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum with complete median longitudinal division. Metanotal median triangle weakly indicated; median reticles elongate with thick flattened walls, medial setae minute. Meso and metathoracic furca transverse. Forewing base broad (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1270,457,483]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[1237,1270,457,483]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
), veinal setae scarcely larger than microtrichia; costal cilia longer than wing width. Abdominal tergite II with pair of submedian transverse depressions filled with microtrichia, laterally these depressions are very weakly S-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[160,249,573,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[216,249,573,599]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
); tergites III–VII with paired lateral invaginations filled with microtrichia that also extend medially onto sculpture lines (
<figureCitation box="[405,493,612,638]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[462,493,612,638]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
); III–VIII with pair of sigmoidal setae (weak on VIII) (
<figureCitation box="[1165,1304,612,638]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Figs 
<number box="[1227,1304,612,638]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="10.11">10, 11</number>
</figureCitation>
); VII–VIII with one setae medially on antecostal ridge (
<figureCitation box="[700,790,650,676]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,271,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,389,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[188,1398,389,2002]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 12. Bhattithrips borealis. (7) female. (8) antenna. (9) head and pronotum. (10) abdominal tergites I – III." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191441/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[758,790,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
); IX with setae S 
<number box="[1003,1019,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="2.0">2</number>
about twice as long as S 
<number box="[1329,1342,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="1.0">1</number>
, but S 
<number box="[1421,1436,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="31" value="3.0">3</number>
almost half as long as X; tergite X asymmetric, median split complete, terminal setae minute. Sternites with setae arising almost at margin; III–VII with paired circular, stoutly walled, invaginations at dorso-ventral muscle insertions.
</paragraph>
